I. CO2 Trends

First read in the data and get it ready to use You can find the data and read more about it here: https://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/carbon-dioxide/ In particular, the metadata is at the top of the txt file if you click on the Download Data button

Helpful hint: CO2 is changing over time, but also changes cyclically throughout the year. Consequently, the data are reported both for monthly values and deseasonalized values that remove the seasonal trend. Think about how you would use this to look at trends over long time periods, and also to isolate the strength of the monthly effect.

To get you started heres the code to read in the data and give it better column names

CO2data <- fread('ftp://aftp.cmdl.noaa.gov/products/trends/co2/co2_mm_mlo.txt', skip = 71)

# give descriptive but short names
names(CO2data) <- c("year", "month", "decimalDate", "monthlyCO2", "deseasonalizedCO2",  "numberDays", "stddev", "uncertainty")

  1. Read about the data
    Why are there two different columns for CO2? Where do the data come from? What does numberDays refer to? What does -9.99 in the stddev column and -1 in the number of days column mean? One column is for monthly CO2 values corrected based on the average seasonal cycle. Deseasonalized CO2 centered to remove seasonal effect. numberDays refers to missing days. There is some missing information for the numberDays and stddev which was taken from SIO from 1958-1974. So, the -9.99 in the stddev column and -1 in the number of days column indicate this missing information and is a sort of placeholder.

  2. Visualize the data: How do atmospheric CO2 concentrations change over the time series? The atmospheric [CO2] increases over time.

  1. Describe your process: What category of graph will you use? What statistical transformation will you use? Does the underlying data differ if you use the monthly or deseasonalized columns? Does the statistical transformation differ if you use the monthly or deseasonalized columns?
    I wanted to use geom_line() from ggplot and also labs() to create labels. The underlying data is unchanged when using monthly or deseasonalized CO2, but switching between the two in the transformation changes since you are plotting different things.

  2. Graph it:

ggplot(CO2data, aes(x=decimalDate, y=monthlyCO2)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  labs(x="Date", y="monthlyCO2") +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se=F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  1. Visualize the data: Which months are the CO2 values at the maximum? Minimum? Why is this?
    May has the maximum CO2 value and September/October has the minimum. During early spring, CO2 is released through respiration resulting in a CO2 bloom that peaks in May. Conversely, the fall season occurs after summer, when there is a peak in photosynthesis and CO2. Thus, the minimum [CO2] is during early fall. Source: https://airs.jpl.nasa.gov/resources/122/watching-earth-breathe-the-seasonal-vegetation-cycle-and-atmospheric-carbon-dioxide/

  1. Describe your process: What category of graph will you use? What statistical transformation will you use?
    I used a box plot. On the y-axis, I put the difference between the monthly and deseasonalized CO2 to remove the difference between 1960 and 2020. The amount of variation between the long-term trend (highlighted in the deseasonalizedCO2) and the actual amount of CO2 should be similar between 1960 and 2020. CO2 levels have risen since data collection started, and I want to isolate the trend of CO2 values over the course of a general year. Here is what worked for me:

# Working method
ggplot(CO2data, aes(x=as.factor(month), y=(monthlyCO2-deseasonalizedCO2))) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(group = cut_width(month, 0.25)), outlier.alpha = 0.1) + 
    labs(title="Box plot", 
         subtitle="MontlyCO2 per Month",
         caption="Source: mpg",
         x="Months",
         y="CO2 amount")

From left to right, the columns are Year, No_Smoothing, and Lowess. The No_Smoothing column shows the unadjusted annual mean for the global temperature. The Lowess column fits the data to a line through a time-based plot like tempdata. The data comes from NASAs Goddard Institute for Space Studies (GISS).

  1. Recreate the graph on the website using all three columns
ggplot(tempdata, aes(x=year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y=Lowess, color = "Lowess smoothing")) + 
  geom_line(aes(y=No_Smoothing, color = "Annual Mean")) +

III. Ice sheets

Have a look at the following data, and read it into R Either use fread() in library(data.table) to read it from the web, or read.csv()

Data description: http://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/land-ice/ Raw data file: http://climate.nasa.gov/system/internal_resources/details/original/499_GRN_ANT_mass_changes.csv

# Run the following to read the .csv from the web and rename columns
icedat0 <- fread('http://climate.nasa.gov/system/internal_resources/details/original/499_GRN_ANT_mass_changes.csv')

icedat <- icedat0[-c(1:10),]
names(icedat) = c("year_decimal", "Greenlandmass_Gt", "Antarcticamass_Gt")
icedat$year_decimal <- as.numeric(icedat$year_decimal)
icedat$Greenlandmass_Gt <- as.numeric(icedat$Greenlandmass_Gt)
icedat$Antarcticamass_Gt <- as.numeric(icedat$Antarcticamass_Gt)

  1. Describe the data set: What are the columns and units? Where do the numbers come from? What is the uncertainty in measurement? The data set includes ice mass measurements by NASAs GRACE satellites. The columns (from left to right) is Time by decimal year, Greenlands ice mass in Gigatonnes, and Antarcticas ice mass in Gigatonnes. There are measurements for Antarctica and Greenland. There is some uncertainty due to unrecorded data from June 11, 2017 to July 13, 2018, which was from a gap between missions.

  2. Plot the data and describe the trends you observe. The ice mass in both locations have been decreasing since the data collection began and until it ended at the end of 2014. Also, the rate that Greenland is losing ice mass is greater than Antarctica.

ggplot(icedat, aes(x= year_decimal)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=Greenlandmass_Gt, color = "Greenland")) +
  geom_smooth(aes(y=Greenlandmass_Gt, color = "Greenland"), method="lm", se=F, color = "grey") +
  geom_line(aes(y=Antarcticamass_Gt, color = "Antarctica")) +
  geom_smooth(aes(y=Antarcticamass_Gt, color = "Greenland"), method="lm", se=F, color = "grey") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    'Greenland' = 'red',
    'Antarctica' = 'blue')) +
  labs(title="MASS VARIATION SINCE 2002", 
       color = "Legend",
       subtitle="Data source: Ice mass measurement by NASA's GRACE satellites 
       Note: Gap represents time between missions.
       Credit: NASA",
       y="Mass (Gt)",
       x="Year") # title and caption
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

IV. Sea level

Have a look at the following data, and read it into R Either use fread() in library(data.table) to read it from the web, or read.table() if you download the data and save it as a .txt file. Consider using the skip argument to skip down to the data.

Data description: http://climate.nasa.gov/vital-signs/sea-level/ Raw data file: http://climate.nasa.gov/system/internal_resources/details/original/121_Global_Sea_Level_Data_File.txt

# Run the following to read the .txt from the web and rename columns
seadata <- fread('http://climate.nasa.gov/system/internal_resources/details/original/121_Global_Sea_Level_Data_File.txt', skip = 47)

names(seadata) = c("altimeter", "cyclenum", "yeardecimal", "observnum", "weighted_obsvnum", "GMSL_nonGIA", "stdev_GMSL_nonGia", "smooth_GMSL_nonGia", "GMSL_GIA", "stdev_GMSL_Gia", "smooth_GMSL", "smooth_GMSL_rmsig")

# head(seadata)
  1. Describe the data set: What are the columns and units? Where do the numbers come from? What is the uncertainty in measurement?

From left to right: alimeter type, the merged file cycle number, the date in decimal-year form, the number of observations, number of weighted observations, GMSL (Global Isostatic Adjustment (GIA) not applied) variation (in mm), standard deviation of GMSL (GIA not applied) variation (in mm), the smoothed GMSL (GIA not applied) variation (in mm), GMSL (GIA applied) variation (in mm),the standard deviation of GMSL (GIA applied) variation (in mm), the smoothed GMSL (GIA applied) variation (in mm), the smoothed GMSL (GIA applied) variation (in mm) WITH the annual and semi-annual signal removed.

The Global Mean Sea Level (GMSL) numbers come from the NASA Goddard Space Flight Center and is from the Integrated Multi-Mission Ocean Altimeter Data for Climate Research. To make the data record consistent (since different instruments are used), the GMSL combines the sea level measurements to a common terrestrial reference frame with all inter-mission biases, range and geophysical corrections applied and placed onto a georeferenced orbit. (Beckley, et al. 2010).

The uncertainty shown in the standard deviation. In the webpage for Sea Level, the graph shows a solid black line and a faint blue highlight around the black line. The blue line shows the amount of error and that the uncertainty is consistently one value

  1. Plot the data and describe the trends you observe. Overall, sea levels are increasing and have been increasing since the start of the data collection. Also within a year, there is a cyclical-like line showing that the sea levels vary based on the time of year.
# Global Mean Sea Level (GMSL) to linear trendline
ggplot(seadata, aes(x= yeardecimal)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=GMSL_GIA), color = "black") +
  geom_smooth(aes(y=GMSL_GIA), method = "lm") +
  labs(title="Global Mean Sea Level (GMSL)",
       subtitle="Data source: Satellite sea level observations.
       Credit: NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center",
       y="GMSL variations (mm)",
       x="Year") # title and caption
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

#over one year
ggplot(seadata, aes(x= yeardecimal)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=GMSL_GIA), color = "black") +
  geom_smooth(aes(y=GMSL_GIA)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(2000, 2001)) +
  labs(title="Global Mean Sea Level (GMSL)",
       subtitle="Data source: Satellite sea level observations.
       Credit: NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center",
       y="GMSL variations (mm)",
       x="Year") # title and caption
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 810 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 810 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

# Global Mean Sea Level (GMSL) with std deviation highlighted
ggplot(seadata, aes(x= yeardecimal)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=GMSL_GIA)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(y = GMSL_GIA, ymin = (GMSL_GIA - (0.5*stdev_GMSL_Gia)), ymax = (GMSL_GIA + (0.5*stdev_GMSL_Gia))), alpha = .2) +
  labs(title="Global Mean Sea Level (GMSL) with std deviation",
       subtitle="Data source: Satellite sea level observations.
       Credit: NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center",
       y="GMSL variations (mm)",
       x="Year") # title and caption

# smooth_GMSL vs smooth_GMSL signal removed
ggplot(seadata, aes(x= yeardecimal)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=smooth_GMSL, color = "Smoothed GMSL")) +
  geom_line(aes(y=smooth_GMSL_rmsig, color = "Smoothed GMSL, 
                annual and semi-annual signal removed")) +
  labs(title="Smoothed GMSL vs Smooth GMSL with signal removed",
       subtitle="Data source: Satellite sea level observations.
       Credit: NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center",
       color = "Legend",
       y="Smoothed GMSL variation (mm)",
       x="Year") # title and caption

V. Longer term CO2 trends

Have a look at the following data, and read it into R Either use fread() in library(data.table) to read it from the web, or read.table() if you download the data and save as a .txt file.

Description of data set: https://cdiac.ess-dive.lbl.gov/trends/co2/vostok.html Data source: https://cdiac.ess-dive.lbl.gov/ftp/trends/co2/vostok.icecore.co2

# Run the following to read the .txt from the web and rename columns
longCO2 <- fread('https://cdiac.ess-dive.lbl.gov/ftp/trends/co2/vostok.icecore.co2', skip = 16)

names(longCO2) = c("depth", "age_of_ice", "mean_air_age", "CO2conc")

head(longCO2)
##    depth age_of_ice mean_air_age CO2conc
## 1: 149.1       5679         2342   284.7
## 2: 173.1       6828         3634   272.8
## 3: 177.4       7043         3833   268.1
## 4: 228.6       9523         6220   262.2
## 5: 250.3      10579         7327   254.6
## 6: 266.0      11334         8113   259.6

  1. Describe the data set: What are the columns and units? Where do the numbers come from? From left to right, the columns are: the ice depth (m), age of the ice (year BP) mean age of the air (year BP), and CO2 concentration (ppmv). The data comes from the Historical CO2 Record from the Vostok Ice Core. During a collaborative project, Russia, the US, and France yielded the deepest ice core ever recovered (Barnola, et. al, 2003).

  2. Plot the data and describe the trends you observe. Please both assess the relationship between depth and age, and between those variables and CO2. If you would like to reverse the order on the x axis (so that values go from deep to shallow and old to young), add the following to the ggplot line: + scale_x_continuous(trans = reverse) As we go deeper into the ice core, the older the ice is. Looking at the relationship between depth and CO2 concentrations, as well as the age of the ice and CO2 concentrations, we see that the CO2 concentrations follow a cyclical pattern. Also, the cyclical trend in [CO2] are similar for each glacial cycle (Barnola, et. al, 2003). 

ggplot(longCO2, aes(x= depth)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=age_of_ice), color = "black") + 
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "reverse") +
  labs(title= "Ice Depth vs Age of Ice",
       subtitle="Data source: Historical CO2 Record from the Vostok Ice Core.
       Credit: Barnola, J.-M., D. Raynaud, C. Lorius, and N.I. Barkov. 2003.",
       y="Age of Ice (yr BP)",
       x="Depth (m)") # title and caption

ggplot(longCO2, aes(x= age_of_ice)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=CO2conc), color = "black") +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = "reverse") +
  labs(title="Age of Ice vs [CO2]",
       subtitle="Data source: Historical CO2 Record from the Vostok Ice Core.
       Credit: Barnola, J.-M., D. Raynaud, C. Lorius, and N.I. Barkov. 2003.",
       y="[CO2] (ppmv)",
       x="Age of Ice (yr BP)") # title and caption
